      <tr>
        <td bgcolor='black' valign=top width='100' nowrap><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'><b>Kriista</b></font></td>
        <td bgcolor='black' valign='top' width='100%'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> it occured to me today, that alot of necros dont...., pull</P><P>that is, exclusively, for xp groups</P><P>now, for some reason typical xp groups like having melee pull</P><P>which makes for unneeded downtime between mobs, OR watered down dps before/after a mob dies whlie a monk or something goes to get soemthing</P><P>as a necro, rather, as a dot class, i can bring a mob, drop dots/epic in and work on pulling/splitting another one</P><P>not to mention being able to mez my own pulls(saves cleric mana)</P><P><BR>i shall use CT camps as examples of diff pull techniques, since it provides a nice assortment of pulling problems, that coupled with how fucking hard the mobs hit and immunities makes for a hella learning experience<BR>and besides, most people prolly hvae the impression that you NEED a lvl 60 MONK to pull in CT for you, /shrug, to each their own</P><P><BR>1st off, pulling tools :</P><P>believe or not, unless your talking bout PURE melee/fd pulling red con mobs(dragons and such), no class pulls better than a necro (well, a well geared/trained necro), rather, no other class has as many pulling tools available</P><P>root, mez, fear, snare, da, dot, insta invis, FD, dispell,  just to drop a few</P><P>lets take CY in CT for example</P><P>nothing here is immune to ST (cept mebee the named aggressor), generally, for CY mobs i pull with ST , and i know the pathing/roamers well enough to know what to get and when to be able to single pull all of CY</P><P>for those that dont know CT, another example of prime ST pulliing is splitting the ICGs in crypt in seb, id like to see how long it takes a monk/sk to split those 2 fuckers<BR>as a necro, ST one, back other one out, FD, stand once ST clears, cake</P><P>a variation in ST pulling is root pulling<BR>i usually use this further into CT(4c for example) where mobs are immune to ST<BR>my root of choice for this is enstill, ive just had better 'luck' if you will with it, regardless, the question shoudl be between PE and enstill, immobilize resists too much, root doesnt hold long enough<BR>lets take 4c, now, once oyu get up into 4c, and have the well, 4 corners to deal with, the corners with see invis are immune to GoK, but a nice combination of root + pure FD split works well here, <BR>i normally root the non doo-doo colored one, and lean againts a wall to channel FD(also make sure nothing is casting, as a wasted FD in CT = death)</P><P>whenever possible i like to use walls/corners to FD againts, that ensures one axis will make the check for chaneling(well, has a better chance to)</P><P><BR>lets take kael arena, again, for those not familiar with CT , splitting PoZs, these are a bitch to split for a monk/sk(well, not a bitch) but requires a bit of flopping and use of geometry<BR>as a necro, root one, back other up, FD until root clears, done</P><P>snare pull/splitting</P><P>some of you may remember Sally's post on single pulling the arch inspector, <BR>well, teh concept is simple a snared mob, does not move(return to spawn)<BR>so..., you can use this to split mobs from sets</P><P>lets take ltae as an example here</P><P>the throne room has 3 mobs, 2 monkeys and 1 lizard, rather than use ST/root to turn that into 2 and use pure FD + tagger to get a single i find that using snare works best here(i have epic, which helps alot since i can FD immiately after casting, which is important)</P><P>target the one you want, cast epic, back up a bit, what you want to do here is have the snared mob far enough from his spawn so that when the 2 non snared mobs return to spawn, they wont assist<BR>it might take 2 tries to get him out of theyre assist range, but its a nice method for splitting mobs like these</P><P>now, i havent done much with DA pulling, but then again, i havent done any pulling in tov and such, when i do, i will put that to use</P><P>for invis, ill just use a simple example of how this is usefull</P><P>acrylia, named mob is up, zone is full pop, you want the named mob</P><P>k, not a difficult concept to explain here, cast a spell on the mob, invis and run, given the tiny assist range here, youll have the mob at zone line(or RoF if thats where your pulling) solo, in no time<BR>another variation on tihs is to root the mob at spawn, then cast invis, then run, having insta cast just makes it easier</P><P><BR>how to 'tag' mobs that you arent pulling via proximity + root/st</P><P><BR>if youve spent any time pulling, youll notice that simeple things like, /conning mobs increases theyre aggro range, same goes for /hailing them<BR>it may sound funny, but try it<BR>target a mob, /con it, watch it move(or turn), im not exactly sure what just took place, but it happens even if you /con indifferent(while being invis)<BR>what i suspect is when you /con a mob, its /conning you, checking faction/lvl/assist/aggro range</P><P>anotherthing, if you run into a mob, and back away real fast, chances are, you will not have gotten aggro</P><P>so tehres a tiny 'window of opportunity' there,</P><P>lets take CT sewers for an example, mots everything there comes in 2s, and some points 3s, i pull here just using proximity + /con + /hail<BR>when done right you can control what you get, <BR>example, theres a goo in the hall(past 1st 3pop room), with a bug within its (pathing) assist range</P><P>if you cast a spell on this goo, youll have 2 mobs chasing you, because the pathing makes the goo walk INTO the bugs assist range, THEN come after you</P><P>if you inch up and /con pull it, hell come directly toward you, coming single</P><P>theres a very big 'grey' area here, when talking about LoS, assist/aggro rangers, /con, /hail, and proximity pulling<BR>huge amounts of variables, that you really have to have alot of experience pulling certain zone/mobs to get the hang of, just realize these concepts and youll be better off</P><P>how to handle single pull mobs with spells<BR>i think 'tag' spell choice is something thats pretty important<BR>in normal xp zones(HS, seb etc..) defluxs work well for pulling, fast casting, and they dont require another gem, in HS i always pull iwth slow, makes shit nicer for when it gets there, </P><P>also, ANY damage done to a mob in order to pull it aggrivates its assist range( have a monk pull juggz in seb, and see how many you need to split), then go hvae someone pull wiht dispell and see how many come solo/double), </P><P>again, back to CT as i view this as a pulling 'right of passage', <BR>as in, you cant fuck around, and discicions you make on the fly are life/death foryourself and your party</P><P>in CT you can NOT pull with deflux, your going to get adds, your going to get summoned, and your going to die</P><P>the spells i use to 'tag' with in CT are :<BR> <BR>dispell:(ONLY when pulling purely non casters(goos/bugs etc..)), if you use dispell on caster mobs, they stop to rebuff totally throwing your tag/pathing<BR>siphon str: good cast time, no mana cost, no damage, and low aggro<BR>shadow vortex : similar, but more aggro tied to this one<BR>scent of terris : alot of mana and aggro, but usefull if oyu plan on ebolting at all(also, i can imagine a VS staff helps here, if oyu dont mind the hp loss)</P><P>now alot of you might wonder, why worry bout single pulling mobs when you have a chanter</P><P>well, if you hvae a melee pulling, you want to constantly have 2+ mobs at your camp, since theres downtime involved in melee pulling</P><P>for necro pulling, theres no downtime at all, when a mob dies, theres one to replace it, the chanter is busy enough trying to manage aggro from tash/slowing shit, he doesnt he 3 mobs to worry bout mezzing, esp since these things put out sick damage, it makes for undeeded down time(cleric is blowing mana healing the chanter/tanks getting hit, chanter is blowing mana holding GoK mobs for long amounts of time)</P><P>also, once i put my dots in, my damage is being done for me during the fight, when i get back ill ToN/flux a bit to cap mobs off(fury3 helps here)<BR>so tehres no diluted dps from me, without pyre my dps isnt much(splurt, vex, pyro, epic), but the dps + utility of the CONSTANT pulling makes the necro an extremely valuable asset</P><P>im not much for healing myself, but i usualy throw around some Zveefers (CT is a huge drain on cleric mana since chanters eat hits life mofos here, not to mention unmezable mobs), if i had the gems to spell, id keep shadowbond up too to help out a bit</P><P>as mentioned earlier, the ability to mez your own pulls is big<BR>i can comfortably bring 2-3 mobs(in CT) to a camp and know well be ok, ill ST whatever is lowest lvl till chanter gets a lockdown going<BR>once you group with a specific chanter enough, and learn each others abilities/styles you get an extremely effecient CC unit going</P><P>now, i do have above average hp (2226 unbuffed, so im usually around 3500hp depending on if theres a shammy or pally to buff), so i woudlnt reccomend doing this with 1400hp unbuffed or so, youll get waxed, that is, in CT</P><P><BR>oh, i complete left out non spell based pulling tactics, like using LoS to split mobs that cast, geometry to split pathers(going back) and such, but go over to monkly-business i think theres a nice writeup on taht sort of pulling in there somewhere<BR>real handy to know</P><P><BR>there ya go, another nifty guide</P><P></P><P>Kriista Silence<BR>Warlock of Veeshan</P><P><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=103458" target="_blank">http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=103458</a></font></td>
