        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> <BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=2 face="Verdana" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR>if you cast a no dmg spell on the one you don't want and then run back a little ways and FD, the one you cast on will return to his spawn point while the one didn't cast on will stay on you.<BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana" size=2 id=quote></P><P>This works both ways. If you pull with a dot (ie, snare), run away, then FD, the mobs that weren't dotted will go back to spawn point sooner. The one with the dot won't go back to spawn until the spell wears off.</P><P>Must have something to do with the act of a spell wearing off or otherwise not effecting the mob resetting it's AI so it can go back to the spawn point.</P><P>Your way works fine with two mobs, but pulling with a long duration dot (disease cloud anyone? ;) can make getting a single out of many much easier.</P><P>This, incidentially, is why I think SK's (or necros) make better pullers than monks, especially when a single pull is important. All monks really have going for them is an insta cast, uninterruptable FD.</P><P><a href="http://tru7h.org/absor/" target="_blank">http://tru7h.org/absor/</a> -  ask absor anything!<BR><a href="http://xzzy.org/ereet/" target="_blank">http://xzzy.org/ereet/</a></font></td>
